Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Riemannian Geometry and Approximate Fisher Metrics

Let \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^d be an open parameter manifold. For a probabilistic model p_\theta(x) differentiable in \theta, the Fisher information metric is the matrix g_F(\theta) \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d} with entries

[g_F(\theta)]_{ij} = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim p_\theta}\left[\frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta_i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta_j}\right].

Under mild regularity conditions, g_F(\theta) is symmetric positive semi‑definite. We assume throughout that g_F(\theta) \succ 0 uniformly on \Theta, making (\Theta, g_F) a Riemannian manifold. The inner product on the tangent space T_\theta \Theta is \langle u, v \rangle_{g_F} = u^\top g_F(\theta) v.

Definition 2.1 (Natural Gradient). The natural gradient of a differentiable function f: \Theta \to \mathbb{R} is

\nabla^F f(\theta) = g_F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla f(\theta),

where \nabla f(\theta) is the standard Euclidean gradient. The natural gradient is the steepest ascent direction under the Fisher metric and is invariant under smooth reparameterization.

Definition 2.2 (Geodesic Distance). The geodesic distance d_F(\theta_1, \theta_2) is the infimum of the length of curves \gamma: [0,1] \to \Theta with \gamma(0) = \theta_1, \gamma(1) = \theta_2, where length is measured with respect to g_F.

Definition 2.3 (K‑FAC Approximation). In large‑scale deep learning, exact inversion of g_F(\theta) is intractable. The Kronecker‑Factored Approximate Curvature (K‑FAC, Martens & Grosse, 2015) approximates g_F(\theta) by a block‑diagonal matrix \hat{g}_F(\theta). We assume there exists a constant \delta_{\text{KFAC}} \ge 0 such that

\|\hat{g}_F(\theta)^{-1} - g_F(\theta)^{-1}\|_{\text{op}} \le \delta_{\text{KFAC}} \quad \forall \theta \in \Theta,

where \|\cdot\|_{\text{op}} denotes the operator norm induced by the Euclidean norm.

Lemma 2.1 (Perturbation of Natural Gradient). Let \Psi(\theta) = -g_F^{-1}\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta) and \hat{\Psi}(\theta) = -\hat{g}_F^{-1}\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta). Then

\|\Psi(\theta) - \hat{\Psi}(\theta)\| \le \delta_{\text{KFAC}} \|\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta)\|.

Proof. Immediate from the definition of operator norm and the fact that \Psi - \hat{\Psi} = (g_F^{-1} - \hat{g}_F^{-1})\nabla \mathcal{L}. \square

2.2 The K‑Stale InfoNCE Surrogate and Its Regularity

We now define the concrete surrogate for the Maakoul constraint and rigorously establish its regularity.

Definition 2.4 (InfoNCE Bound). Let Z_\theta be the latent representation produced by the encoder with parameters \theta. Let R_{\text{rare}} \in \{0,1\} be a binary indicator of a rare event. Given a critic network T_\psi : \mathcal{Z} \times \{0,1\} \to \mathbb{R}, the InfoNCE lower bound on mutual information is

\hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) = \mathbb{E}_{(z, r^+) \sim p_\theta(z, r)} \left[ \log \frac{e^{T_\psi(z, r^+)}}{\frac{1}{K}\sum_{j=1}^K e^{T_\psi(z, r_j)}} \right],

where r_j are independent samples from the marginal p(r), and K \ge 1 is the number of negative samples. It is known that \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) \le I(Z_\theta; R_{\text{rare}}) for any \psi, with equality when the critic is optimal (Oord et al., 2018).

Assumption 2.1 (Encoder and Critic Regularity).

· The encoder Z_\theta is implemented as a recurrent neural network (e.g., GRU). We assume gradients are computed via truncated backpropagation through time with horizon H. Consequently, there exist constants L_z(H) and L_{z2}(H) such that for all \theta in any compact set and for almost all input sequences x, \|D_\theta Z_\theta(x)\| \le L_z(H) and \|D^2_\theta Z_\theta(x)\| \le L_{z2}(H).
· The critic T_\psi(z, r) is a two‑layer MLP with Swish activation (or any C^2 activation with bounded derivatives). For fixed \psi, the function z \mapsto T_\psi(z, r) is C^2, with \|T_\psi\|_\infty \le T_{\max}, \|\nabla_z T_\psi\| \le L_T, and \|D^2_z T_\psi\| \le L_{T2}.

Lemma 2.2 (Regularity of K‑Stale InfoNCE under Truncated BPTT). Under Assumption 2.1, for fixed \psi, the function \theta \mapsto \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) is locally Lipschitz and almost everywhere differentiable. Moreover, wherever the derivative exists, it is given by

\nabla_\theta \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) = \mathbb{E}_{(x, r^+), \{r_j\}} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log \frac{e^{T_\psi(Z_\theta(x), r^+)}}{\frac{1}{K}\sum_{j=1}^K e^{T_\psi(Z_\theta(x), r_j)}} \right],

and on any compact set \mathcal{K} \subset \Theta, there exists a constant L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) such that for all \theta_1, \theta_2 \in \mathcal{K},

\|\nabla_\theta \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta_1; \psi) - \nabla_\theta \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta_2; \psi)\| \le L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) \|\theta_1 - \theta_2\|.

Proof. Define F(\theta, \omega) = \log \frac{e^{T_\psi(Z_\theta(x), r^+)}}{\frac{1}{K}\sum_{j=1}^K e^{T_\psi(Z_\theta(x), r_j)}}, where \omega = (x, r^+, r_1, \dots, r_K). For fixed \omega, F is a composition of smooth functions and is C^2 in \theta because truncated BPTT yields a finite computation graph. The gradient with respect to \theta is

\nabla_\theta F(\theta, \omega) = (D_\theta Z_\theta(x))^\top \nabla_z F(z, \omega),

where \nabla_z F is the derivative of the log‑softmax with respect to the latent z = Z_\theta(x). By the properties of the softmax function and the boundedness of T_\psi, we have \|\nabla_z F\| \le 2 L_T.

We now establish a dominating function to apply the Dominated Convergence Theorem. Since \|D_\theta Z_\theta(x)\| \le L_z(H) uniformly for all x in the support of the data distribution (which has finite second moments), we have

\|\nabla_\theta F(\theta, \omega)\| \le L_z(H) \cdot 2 L_T.

This bound is uniform in \omega and \theta, and since it is constant, it is integrable. By the Dominated Convergence Theorem, we can exchange differentiation and expectation:

\nabla_\theta \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) = \mathbb{E}_\omega[\nabla_\theta F(\theta, \omega)].

Similarly, for the Hessian, we compute

\nabla_\theta^2 F(\theta, \omega) = (D_\theta Z_\theta)^\top (\nabla_z^2 F) (D_\theta Z_\theta) + (D^2_\theta Z_\theta) \cdot \nabla_z F.

The Hessian of the log‑softmax \nabla_z^2 F has operator norm bounded by 4 L_T. Hence,

\|\nabla_\theta^2 F(\theta, \omega)\| \le L_z(H)^2 \cdot 4L_T + L_{z2}(H) \cdot 2L_T =: M(H).

Again, M(H) is a constant and thus integrable. DCT then implies that the gradient is differentiable almost everywhere and its derivative is bounded by M(H) on any compact set. Consequently, the gradient is locally Lipschitz with constant L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) = M(H). \square

Definition 2.5 (K‑Stale InfoNCE Surrogate). We update the critic parameters \psi every K steps using standard gradient ascent on the InfoNCE objective (with respect to \psi). Between critic updates, the function I_{\text{rare}}(\theta) := \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi_k) is locally Lipschitz and almost everywhere differentiable, and serves as the surrogate for the Maakoul constraint. Because \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}} is a lower bound on the true mutual information, preserving this surrogate ensures that the true MI does not decrease below the surrogate's value.

2.3 Control Barrier Functions and Constraint Qualifications

Consider a dynamical system \dot{\theta} = \Psi(\theta) on \Theta. A set \mathcal{C} \subset \Theta is forward invariant if for any initial condition \theta_0 \in \mathcal{C}, the trajectory \theta_t remains in \mathcal{C} for all t \ge 0.

Definition 2.6 (Control Barrier Function). Let \mathcal{C} = \{\theta \in \Theta : h(\theta) \ge 0\} for a continuously differentiable function h: \Theta \to \mathbb{R}. The function h is a Control Barrier Function (CBF) for the system if there exists a class‑\mathcal{K} function \alpha (continuous, strictly increasing, \alpha(0) = 0) such that for all \theta \in \mathcal{C},

\langle \nabla h(\theta), \Psi(\theta) \rangle \ge -\alpha(h(\theta)).

Theorem 2.3 (Forward Invariance via CBFs). If h is a CBF for \dot{\theta} = \Psi(\theta) on \mathcal{C}, then \mathcal{C} is forward invariant.

Proof. Define y(t) = h(\theta_t). Its time derivative satisfies \dot{y}(t) = \langle \nabla h(\theta_t), \Psi(\theta_t) \rangle \ge -\alpha(y(t)). By the comparison lemma for ODEs, y(t) \ge z(t) for all t \ge 0, where z(t) solves \dot{z} = -\alpha(z) with z(0) = y(0) = h(\theta_0) \ge 0. Since \alpha is class‑\mathcal{K} and z(0) \ge 0, we have z(t) \ge 0 for all t. Hence y(t) \ge 0, so \theta_t \in \mathcal{C}. \square

Definition 2.7 (Mangasarian‑Fromovitz Constraint Qualification). For the constraints g(\theta) = 0 and h(\theta) \ge 0, MFCQ holds at \theta \in G \cap \partial \mathcal{C} if:

1. The gradients \nabla g_i(\theta) are linearly independent (i.e., \nabla g(\theta) has full column rank).
2. There exists a direction d \in \text{Null}(\nabla g(\theta)^\top) such that \langle \nabla h(\theta), d \rangle > 0.

Example 2.1 (MFCQ for KL Constraints). Let g(\theta) = \text{KL}(p_\theta \| p_0) - \epsilon and h(\theta) = \text{KL}(p_\theta \| p_{\text{unsafe}}) - \delta. At a point where both constraints are active, \nabla g \propto \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}[\nabla_\theta \log p_\theta \cdot \log(p_\theta/p_0)] and \nabla h \propto \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}[\nabla_\theta \log p_\theta \cdot \log(p_\theta/p_{\text{unsafe}})]. MFCQ fails only if \nabla h is collinear with \nabla g, which implies \log(p_\theta/p_{\text{unsafe}}) = c \log(p_\theta/p_0) almost everywhere. For generic reference models p_0 and unsafe models p_{\text{unsafe}}, this condition does not hold; hence MFCQ is satisfied generically.

Example 2.2 (MFCQ Failure: Tangent Norm Balls). Let g(\theta) = \|\theta\|^2 - 1 and h(\theta) = 1 - \|\theta - 2e_1\|^2 where e_1 = (1,0,\dots,0). At \theta = e_1, both constraints are active, \nabla g = 2e_1, \nabla h = -2e_1. Then \nabla h = -\nabla g, so for any d \in T_\theta G (orthogonal to e_1), \langle \nabla h, d \rangle = 0. MFCQ fails. Geometrically, the safe set and alignment manifold are tangent spheres. SRI correctly has no solution, and Theorem 3.6 will certify infeasibility.

Lemma 2.4 (MFCQ Implies Non‑vanishing Projected Safety Gradient). Under MFCQ, the projection of \nabla h(\theta) onto the tangent space T_\theta G (with respect to the Fisher metric) is non‑zero. That is, \Pi_\theta(\nabla h) \neq 0, where \Pi_\theta = I - g_F^{-1}\nabla g (\nabla g^\top g_F^{-1}\nabla g)^{-1}\nabla g^\top is the orthogonal projection onto T_\theta G under g_F.

Proof. Suppose for contradiction that \Pi_\theta(\nabla h) = 0. Then \nabla h \in \text{Range}(\nabla g), i.e., \nabla h = \nabla g \cdot v for some vector v. For any d \in T_\theta G = \text{Null}(\nabla g^\top), we have \langle \nabla h, d \rangle = v^\top \nabla g^\top d = 0. This contradicts the existence of a direction d with \langle \nabla h, d \rangle > 0 required by MFCQ. Hence \Pi_\theta(\nabla h) \neq 0. \square

2.4 Joint Projection onto Alignment and Safety Constraints

We now solve the quadratic program (QP) that projects a proposed vector field onto the intersection of the alignment tangent space and the CBF half‑space.

Lemma 2.5 (Joint Projection under MFCQ). Consider the QP

\Psi^* = \arg\min_{\Psi' \in \mathbb{R}^d} \frac{1}{2}\|\Psi' - \Psi\|_{g_F}^2 \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \nabla g(\theta)^\top \Psi' = 0, \quad \langle \nabla h(\theta), \Psi' \rangle \ge -\alpha(h(\theta)).

Assume MFCQ holds at \theta. Let \Pi_\theta denote the orthogonal projection onto T_\theta G with respect to the Fisher metric g_F. Define

\nu = \max\left(0, \frac{-\alpha(h) - \langle \nabla h, \Pi_\theta(\Psi) \rangle}{\|\Pi_\theta(\nabla h)\|_{g_F}^2}\right).

Then the unique solution is

\Psi^* = \Pi_\theta(\Psi) + \nu \Pi_\theta(\nabla h).

Proof. The Lagrangian is

L(\Psi', \mu, \lambda) = \frac{1}{2}\|\Psi' - \Psi\|_{g_F}^2 + \mu^\top \nabla g^\top \Psi' + \lambda(-\alpha(h) - \langle \nabla h, \Psi' \rangle),

with \lambda \ge 0. Stationarity yields

g_F(\Psi' - \Psi) + \nabla g \mu - \lambda \nabla h = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \Psi' = \Psi - g_F^{-1}\nabla g \mu + \lambda g_F^{-1}\nabla h.

The equality constraint \nabla g^\top \Psi' = 0 determines \mu:

\nabla g^\top \Psi - \nabla g^\top g_F^{-1}\nabla g \mu + \lambda \nabla g^\top g_F^{-1}\nabla h = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \mu = (\nabla g^\top g_F^{-1}\nabla g)^{-1}(\nabla g^\top \Psi + \lambda \nabla g^\top g_F^{-1}\nabla h).

Substituting back gives

\Psi' = \Pi_\theta(\Psi) + \lambda \Pi_\theta(\nabla h).

The CBF constraint is \langle \nabla h, \Psi' \rangle \ge -\alpha(h). Substituting,

\langle \nabla h, \Pi_\theta(\Psi) \rangle + \lambda \langle \nabla h, \Pi_\theta(\nabla h) \rangle \ge -\alpha(h).

By Lemma 2.4, \|\Pi_\theta(\nabla h)\|_{g_F}^2 = \langle \nabla h, \Pi_\theta(\nabla h) \rangle > 0. Therefore, the smallest \lambda \ge 0 satisfying the inequality is exactly the \nu defined above. By complementary slackness, if the unconstrained projection already satisfies the CBF condition, \nu = 0; otherwise \nu > 0 and the constraint is tight. \square

2.5 Manifold‑Constrained Optimization and Nagumo's Theorem

Let G = \{\theta \in \Theta : g(\theta) = 0\} be a smooth submanifold of codimension k, where g: \Theta \to \mathbb{R}^k is C^2 with full‑rank Jacobian \nabla g(\theta) \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times k} on G. The tangent space at \theta \in G is

T_\theta G = \{v \in \mathbb{R}^d : \nabla g(\theta)^\top v = 0\}.

Theorem 2.6 (Nagumo's Invariance Theorem). If \Psi(\theta) \in T_\theta G for all \theta \in G, then any trajectory of \dot{\theta} = \Psi(\theta) starting in G remains in G for all t \ge 0.

Proof. See Nagumo (1942) or standard texts on differential equations on manifolds. \square

2.6 Stochastic Approximation and Supermartingales

We work on a probability space (\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mathbb{P}) equipped with a filtration \{\mathcal{F}_k\}_{k \in \mathbb{N}}. A sequence \{X_k\} adapted to \{\mathcal{F}_k\} is a supermartingale if \mathbb{E}[X_{k+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le X_k almost surely.

Theorem 2.7 (Doob's Martingale Convergence). If \{X_k\} is a non‑negative supermartingale, then X_k converges almost surely to a finite limit X_\infty with \mathbb{E}[X_\infty] \le \mathbb{E}[X_0].

Lemma 2.8 (Hoeffding's Inequality for Martingale Differences). Let \{D_k\} be a sequence of martingale differences adapted to \{\mathcal{F}_k\} with |D_k| \le c_k almost surely. Then for any \tau > 0,

\mathbb{P}\left(\sum_{i=1}^k D_i \ge \tau\right) \le \exp\left(-\frac{2\tau^2}{\sum_{i=1}^k c_i^2}\right).

2.7 Backward Error Analysis for Natural Gradient

To make the Robust Dominance Theorem independent of gradient scale, we use a relative margin formulation.

Definition 2.8 (Relative Margin). We say that the exact composite vector field \Psi_{\text{comp}} = -\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} + \lambda \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} satisfies the Dominance Lemma with relative margin \tilde{\eta} > 0 if

\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \le -\tilde{\eta} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2,

\langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \ge \tilde{\eta} \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2.

This formulation scales the margin with the gradient norm, which is natural for optimization algorithms and yields a scale‑invariant robustness certificate.

