Chapter 3: The Stable Recursive Intelligence Framework (Continuous‑Time)

3.1 Formal Setup and Assumptions

Assumption 3.1 (Smoothness).

· \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} \in C^2(\Theta), bounded below by \mathcal{L}^*, with L-Lipschitz gradient.
· The surrogate I_{\text{rare}}(\theta) = \hat{I}_{\text{NCE}}(\theta; \psi) is locally Lipschitz and a.e. differentiable, with local Lipschitz constant L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) on compact sets (Lemma 2.2).
· g \in C^2(\Theta, \mathbb{R}^k), \nabla g full rank on G.
· h \in C^2(\Theta), \nabla h \neq 0 on \partial \mathcal{C}.
· g_F(\theta) \succ 0 uniformly, with condition number bounded by \kappa.

Assumption 3.2 (MFCQ). The Mangasarian‑Fromovitz constraint qualification (Definition 2.7) holds at every \theta \in G \cap \partial \mathcal{C}.

Assumption 3.3 (Non‑vanishing Capability Gradient). There exists \gamma > 0 such that \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta)\|_{g_F} \ge \gamma for all \theta \in \mathcal{C} \cap G.

3.2 The Dominance Lemma

Lemma 3.1 (Dominance Lemma). Let \lambda \ge 0. Define

\Psi_{\text{comp}}(\theta) = -\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta) + \lambda \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}(\theta).

Then:

· If \langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F} \le 0, then for any \lambda \ge 0,

\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \le -\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2, \quad \langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \ge \lambda \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2 \ge 0.

· If \langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F} > 0, then capability descent requires \lambda < \lambda_{\max} and MI preservation requires \lambda \ge \lambda_{\min}, where

\lambda_{\min} = \frac{\langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} \rangle_{g_F}}{\|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2}, \quad
\lambda_{\max} = \frac{\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2}{\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F}}.

The interval [\lambda_{\min}, \lambda_{\max}) is non‑empty by Cauchy‑Schwarz, with equality only under perfect alignment.

Proof. Direct computation using the definitions and Cauchy‑Schwarz. \square

Corollary 3.2 (Relative Margin Choice). Choose \lambda as follows: if the inner product is non‑positive, set \lambda = 0. If positive, set \lambda = (1 + \delta) \lambda_{\min} for some \delta \in (0, \frac{\lambda_{\max}}{\lambda_{\min}} - 1). Then the composite vector field satisfies the Dominance Lemma with relative margin

\tilde{\eta} = \min\left(1, \delta \cdot \frac{\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F}^2}{\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2 \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2}\right).

Proof. Substitute the choice into the inner products. \square

3.3 Robust Dominance Under K‑FAC Approximation

Theorem 3.3 (Robust Dominance under K‑FAC). Suppose the exact natural gradients satisfy the Dominance Lemma with relative margin \tilde{\eta} > 0. Let \rho = \frac{\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F}}{\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}} be the cosine similarity, and let \lambda be chosen as in Corollary 3.2. Define

\delta^* = \frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2 \sqrt{\kappa} \left(1 + \lambda \frac{\|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}}{\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}}\right)}.

Using the optimal choice \lambda = (1+\delta)\lambda_{\min} when \rho > 0 and \lambda = 0 otherwise, this simplifies to

\delta^* = \begin{cases}
\frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2 \sqrt{\kappa}} & \text{if } \rho \le 0, \\
\frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2 \sqrt{\kappa} (1 + (1+\delta)\rho)} & \text{if } \rho > 0.
\end{cases}

If \delta_{\text{KFAC}} < \delta^*, then

\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \hat{\Psi}_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \le -\frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2, \quad \langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \hat{\Psi}_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \ge \frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2} \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2.

Proof. Write \hat{\Psi}_{\text{comp}} = \Psi_{\text{comp}} + \Delta, with \Delta = -(g_F^{-1} - \hat{g}_F^{-1})(\nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} - \lambda \nabla I_{\text{rare}}). Then

\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \hat{\Psi}_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} = \langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} + \langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \Delta \rangle_{g_F}.

The first term is \le -\tilde{\eta} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2. For the error term, using Lemma 2.1 and the relationship between Euclidean and Fisher norms (\|\nabla f\| \le \sqrt{\|g_F\|_{\text{op}}} \|\nabla^F f\|_{g_F} and \|g_F^{-1}\nabla f\|_{g_F} = \|\nabla^F f\|_{g_F}), we have

|\langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \Delta \rangle_{g_F}| \le \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} \|\Delta\|_{g_F} \le \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} \cdot \delta_{\text{KFAC}} \sqrt{\kappa} (\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} + \lambda \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}).

Thus, the total is bounded by

-\tilde{\eta} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2 + \delta_{\text{KFAC}} \sqrt{\kappa} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2 \left(1 + \lambda \frac{\|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}}{\|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}}\right).

Setting this \le -\frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2 yields the condition on \delta_{\text{KFAC}}. The MI inequality is analogous. The simplification for the piecewise \delta^* follows by substituting \lambda and using \lambda_{\min} = \rho \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} / \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}. \square

Corollary 3.3.1 (Computable Certificate). The value \delta^* depends only on the relative margin \tilde{\eta}, the condition number \kappa, the chosen excess \delta, and the cosine similarity \rho. All of these can be estimated from the K‑FAC quantities with bounded error. In particular, a conservative lower bound is

\hat{\delta}^* = \frac{\tilde{\eta}}{4 \sqrt{\kappa} (1 + \delta)}.

If \delta_{\text{KFAC}} < \hat{\delta}^*, then the conditions of Theorem 3.3 are guaranteed to hold.

Proof. The worst case for the denominator is when \rho = 1 (perfect alignment), yielding \delta^* \ge \frac{\tilde{\eta}}{2\sqrt{\kappa}(1+(1+\delta))} \ge \frac{\tilde{\eta}}{4\sqrt{\kappa}(1+\delta)}. \square

3.4 Joint Projection and the SRI Vector Field

Definition 3.1 (SRI Vector Field). For each \theta \in \Theta, compute the unconstrained composite vector

\Psi_{\text{comp}}(\theta) = -\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta) + \lambda(\theta) \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}(\theta),

where \lambda(\theta) is chosen according to Corollary 3.2. Then define

\Psi_{\text{SRI}}(\theta) = \arg\min_{\Psi'} \|\Psi' - \Psi_{\text{comp}}\|_{g_F}^2 \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \Psi' \in T_\theta G, \quad \langle \nabla h(\theta), \Psi' \rangle \ge -\alpha(h(\theta)).

Theorem 3.4 (Feasibility of Joint Projection). Under Assumption 3.2 (MFCQ), the feasible set of the QP in Definition 3.1 is non‑empty for all \theta \in G \cap \mathcal{C}. Moreover, the solution is given by Lemma 2.5.

Proof. Immediate from Lemma 2.5 and Lemma 2.4. \square

3.5 The Continuous‑Time SRI Theorem

Theorem 3.5 (Stable Recursive Intelligence — Continuous‑Time). Under Assumptions 3.1–3.3, let \Psi_{\text{SRI}} be defined as in Definition 3.1 with \lambda(\theta) chosen to satisfy the Dominance Lemma with relative margin \tilde{\eta} > 0. Then for any initial condition \theta_0 \in \mathcal{C} \cap G, the unique solution to \dot{\theta} = \Psi_{\text{SRI}}(\theta) satisfies for all t \ge 0:

1. \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta_t) is strictly decreasing.
2. I_{\text{rare}}(\theta_t) is non‑decreasing.
3. \theta_t \in G (alignment invariance).
4. \theta_t \in \mathcal{C} (safety forward invariance).

Proof.

1. Capability descent: By construction, \Psi_{\text{SRI}} is the projection of \Psi_{\text{comp}} onto a convex set. A perturbation argument (Appendix A) shows that the descent condition is preserved with a slightly reduced margin.
2. Maakoul preservation: Similar to above.
3. Alignment invariance: By definition, \Psi_{\text{SRI}}(\theta) \in T_\theta G. Nagumo's theorem (Theorem 2.6) gives \theta_t \in G.
4. Safety: The CBF constraint in the QP ensures \langle \nabla h, \Psi_{\text{SRI}} \rangle \ge -\alpha(h). By Theorem 2.3, \mathcal{C} is forward invariant. \square

3.6 Infeasibility Certificate

A natural question is whether the alignment manifold G and safe set \mathcal{C} intersect. If they do not, no SRI trajectory can exist. We provide a certificate to detect this.

Theorem 3.6 (Infeasibility Certificate). Consider the Lagrangian function

L(\theta, \mu, \lambda) = -h(\theta) + \mu^\top g(\theta).

If there exist multipliers \mu and a scalar \lambda \ge 0 such that \inf_{\theta \in \Theta} L(\theta, \mu, \lambda) > 0, then G \cap \mathcal{C} = \emptyset. For constraints defined by neural networks, this infimum can be lower‑bounded using verification techniques such as \alpha,\beta-CROWN (Xu et al., 2020). The certificate is sound but incomplete: a positive lower bound guarantees infeasibility, but a negative bound does not imply feasibility. For ReLU networks of bounded width, \alpha-CROWN provides tight bounds, making the certificate practically useful.

Proof. If G \cap \mathcal{C} \neq \emptyset, then there exists \theta^* with g(\theta^*) = 0 and h(\theta^*) \ge 0. Then for any \mu, \lambda \ge 0, L(\theta^*, \mu, \lambda) = -h(\theta^*) \le 0. Hence, if the infimum over \theta is strictly positive, no such \theta^* can exist. \square

Remark 3.1. This result turns a potential limitation into a diagnostic tool: before deploying SRI, one can attempt to find a dual certificate proving that the chosen alignment and safety constraints are architecturally incompatible. If such a certificate exists, the constraints must be relaxed or the architecture modified.

