Chapter 4: Discrete‑Time Dynamics with Endogenous Dominance Gap

4.1 Stochastic Update Model

In practice, self‑improvement occurs via discrete parameter updates with stochastic noise:

\theta_{k+1} = \theta_k + \eta_k \hat{\Psi}_k + \xi_k,

where:

· \eta_k \in (0, \bar{\eta}] is the learning rate with \sum_k \eta_k = \infty, \sum_k \eta_k^2 < \infty.
· \hat{\Psi}_k is a stochastic estimate of \Psi_{\text{SRI}}(\theta_k), obtained using mini‑batch gradients and K‑FAC.
· \xi_k is zero‑mean noise: \mathbb{E}[\xi_k \mid \mathcal{F}_k] = 0, \mathbb{E}[\|\xi_k\|^2 \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le \sigma_\xi^2.
· \mathcal{F}_k = \sigma(\theta_0, \xi_0, \dots, \xi_{k-1}).

A verification‑bounded rollback rejects updates that increase the loss beyond a tolerance:

\tilde{\theta}_{k+1} = \begin{cases}
\theta_k + \eta_k \hat{\Psi}_k + \xi_k & \text{if } \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta_k + \eta_k \hat{\Psi}_k + \xi_k) \le \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\theta_k) + \delta_k, \\
\theta_k & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}

Condition 4 requires \mathbb{P}(\text{reject} \mid \mathcal{F}_k) \le \epsilon_k with \epsilon_k \to 0.

4.2 Endogenous Non‑uniform Dominance Gap

We use the same \lambda selection as in the continuous‑time case: \lambda = (1+\delta)\lambda_{\min} when the inner product is positive, else \lambda = 0.

Lemma 4.1 (Endogenous Dominance Gap). With this choice, the Maakoul push satisfies

\langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \Psi_{\text{comp}} \rangle_{g_F} \ge \mu_k,

where

\mu_k = \begin{cases}
0 & \text{if } \langle \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}} \rangle_{g_F} \le 0, \\
\delta \langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} \rangle_{g_F} & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}

Proof. Direct substitution. \square

4.3 Step‑Size Bound for Discrete Maakoul Preservation

Theorem 4.2 (Discrete‑Time Maakoul Preservation). Under the update rule and the \lambda selection above, the expected change in I_{\text{rare}} satisfies

\mathbb{E}[I_{\text{rare}}(\tilde{\theta}_{k+1}) \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \ge I_{\text{rare}}(\tilde{\theta}_k) + \eta_k \mu_k - \frac{L_I(\mathcal{K}, H)}{2} \eta_k^2 (\|\Psi_{\text{comp}}\|_{g_F}^2 + \sigma_\xi^2),

where \mathcal{K} is a compact set containing the trajectory. If \mu_k > 0, the expected MI is non‑decreasing provided

\eta_k \le \frac{2 \mu_k}{L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) (\|\Psi_{\text{comp}}\|_{g_F}^2 + \sigma_\xi^2)}.

Proof. Taylor expansion of I_{\text{rare}} around \theta_k, using the local Lipschitz property (Lemma 2.2). The rollback mechanism only helps. \square

Corollary 4.3 (Stable Step‑Size Bound). In the positive‑alignment case, \mu_k = \delta \langle \nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}, \nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}} \rangle_{g_F} \le \delta \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}. Also, \|\Psi_{\text{comp}}\|_{g_F}^2 \le 2 \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2 + 2 \lambda^2 \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}^2. Using \lambda \approx \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F} / \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}, we get \|\Psi_{\text{comp}}\|_{g_F}^2 \le 4 \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}^2. Thus, the step‑size condition becomes approximately

\eta_k \le \frac{\delta \|\nabla^F I_{\text{rare}}\|_{g_F}}{2 L_I(\mathcal{K}, H) \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}\|_{g_F}},

which is independent of the overall gradient scale. As the capability gradient shrinks near convergence, this bound remains well‑behaved provided the MI gradient does not vanish faster.

4.4 Complete Discrete‑Time SRI Theorem

Theorem 4.4 (Discrete‑Time SRI). Under Assumptions 3.1–3.3, with step sizes \sum \eta_k = \infty, \sum \eta_k^2 < \infty, verification rollback with \epsilon_k \to 0, and the joint projection applied at each step, the following hold almost surely:

1. \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\tilde{\theta}_k) converges to a finite limit.
2. \liminf_{k \to \infty} \|\nabla^F \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}(\tilde{\theta}_k)\|_{g_F} = 0.
3. \mathbb{E}[I_{\text{rare}}(\tilde{\theta}_{k+1}) \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \ge I_{\text{rare}}(\tilde{\theta}_k) for all k.
4. \text{dist}(\tilde{\theta}_k, G) \to 0 and \tilde{\theta}_k \in \mathcal{C} for all k.

Proof. Combine the supermartingale argument for \mathcal{L}_{\text{self}}, the discrete Maakoul preservation (Theorem 4.2), the convergence of projected stochastic approximation (Kushner‑Clark lemma applied to the Riemannian gradient), and the forward invariance of \mathcal{C} under the discrete CBF correction. Full details in Appendix B. \square

